    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-03-25T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-03-25T22:00:00-05:00" n="55"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d55">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/10774: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-03-26T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >March 26, 1930—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 26—3:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>222. My 208, March 21, 11 a.m.<note n="78" xml:id="d55fn78">Not printed.</note>
                    Following from American Consul General at [Hankow]: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“March 25, 11 a.m. The Steamship <hi rend="italic">Ifung</hi> of Yangtze
                            Rapid Steamship Company was fired on at mileage 219 above Hankow from
                            the right bank by about 400 soldiers carrying a red flag with white sun.
                            The soldiers fired about 700 shots from rifles. An armed naval guard on
                            the <hi rend="italic">Ifung</hi> [returned?] the fire with 272 rounds.
                            One enlisted man slightly wounded in left forearm by ricochet fragment.
                            Heavy firing was heard inland at mileage 220 above Hankow.</p>
                        <p>There is no unusual military activity in evidence here at present, and,
                            so far as can be learned, local authorities are depending on Government
                            forces now in north and northwest Hupeh and along the Pinghan Railway in
                            Honan to defend Hankow if the threatened war materializes.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
